long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 239121 Screenshot
Hi, I'm chinese, and in eclipse 4.3.1 jee edition, may there are one erro, that is in the "javadoc display dialog", I would like to display the javadoc for chinese version, but it display the chinese garbled? can any one tell me whay? bacause in v4.2.x it's looks okay!

To clarify terminology: its not a dialog but the javadoc *hover* that renders wrongly.
Moving to JDT/UI for comment.

A reproduction on a project set to use an old jdk1.6.0_17 runtime: 1. Edit project build path and change rt.jar settings as follows: Source attachment: none Javadoc URL: http://download.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/6/docs/zh/api/ 2. Open Javadoc view, insert this code and click in it: FileOutputStream(new File("")); 3. Click Open Attached Javadoc in a Browser
Both Javadoc view and hover display garbled characters but the internal browser displays them correctly. One immediate difference: both Javadoc view and internal browser use an org.eclipse.swt.Browser but the internal browser puts it inside an org.eclipse.ui.internal.browser.BrowserViewer instance.

To correct "One immediate difference: both Javadoc view and internal browser use an org.eclipse.swt.Browser but the internal browser puts it inside an org.eclipse.ui.internal.browser.BrowserViewer instance." may be "One immediate difference: both Javadoc view and hover display use an org.eclipse.swt.Browser but the internal browser puts it inside an org.eclipse.ui.internal.browser.BrowserViewer instance."

Before 4.3, JDT Core [1] used the correct encoding specified in the file (gb2312), but now it seems to ignore it and use some other encoding.
[1] IJavaElement.getAttachedJavadoc(IProgressMonitor)
So, could anyone tell me how to solve the problem?

(In reply to Dani Megert from comment #4) > Before 4.3, JDT Core [1] used the correct encoding specified in the file > (gb2312), but now it seems to ignore it and use some other encoding.
Nope, with the steps given in comment #2, I can reproduce this even with a 4.2 build. There's something about the file content. The way META tag has been written is different from its english counterpart.

Created attachment 239414 Proposed fix
This is a draft patch, which appears to address the issue described in comment #2. But yet to be tested well. I will take this up during M6.

The bug occurred because we were expecting META tag to be 'META' and not 'meta'. I have made changes to make the tag decoding part to be case insensitive.
Fix and test released via:
http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/?id=7100eda84b437a1d2f42be690490198bb0d2e1f0

(In reply to Jayaprakash Arthanareeswaran from comment #9) > http://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.core.git/commit/ > ?id=7100eda84b437a1d2f42be690490198bb0d2e1f0
For the record, the fix could have been simpler by using the following utility method:
org.eclipse.jdt.core.compiler.CharOperation.indexOf(..., boolean isCaseSensitive)
Now that this is already released, I see no need to touch it again. But when opportunity presents itself again, we should consider it.

Test Case:
import java.io.File;
public class X { FileOutputStream x = new FileOutputStream(new File("")); }
======================================================================
Output with 4.4 M6: File FileDescriptor FileOutputStream
FileOutputStream FileWriter
JDK1.0
File, FileDescriptor, FileInputStream
========================================================================
Without the fix.
File FileDescriptor FileOutputStream
FileOutputStream FileWriter
JDK1.0
File, FileDescriptor, FileInputStream
========================================================================
Looks like garbled without the fix.
Verified for 4.4 M6 using build I20140303-1130.
